Is the Anne Hathaway 6.9 joke video real? Viral clip debunked (Image via Getty Images)
 ! 
A video of actor Anne Hathaway laughing at an inappropriate joke is doing its rounds online. In the viral clip, Hathaway was seen talking to American TV host Jon Stewart and she asks him the double entendre joke and then gives the answer herself. However, the clip that is garnering massive attention online is a deepfake video and was created by the use of Artificial Technology.
The viral clip of Hathaway cracking the joke has made several people believe that she did in fact crack the joke on The Daily Show. The video is currently being circulated on social media platforms like Youtube, Instagram, and TikTok and it has managed to amass millions of views.
!
For those unaware the viral clip, which is being used as a deepfake, of Anne Hathaway laughing with host Jon Stewart is from her visit to the show back in 2015.
* * *
Anne Hathaway 6.9 joke video is not real and was created by the use of AI
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
As internet users came across the viral clip of Anne Hathaway cracking the joke, they started sharing hilarious reactions and fell for the fake video too. However, according to _HITC_, this viral clip was created using advanced AI technology in which they copied Hathaway's voice and edited her face to make it seem as if the video is real.
> 
Expand Tweet
> 
Expand Tweet
It is worth noting that this deepfake video used a clip from 2015 when Anne appeared on The Daily Show. During the show, she was talking about her then-latest movie, _Song One_, and laughed about it.
!
In the original clip of The Daily Show, she talked about the plot of the movie _Song One_. She said,
> “And then her little brother who’s 19 calls her up and says ‘I’m dropping out of college’ to become a musician. And she doesn’t react very well and they haven’t spoken for six months and then he gets hit by a car and is in a coma.”
As Anne Hathaway says this, she started laughing at it and Jon Stewart joins in. They  Hathaway's statement for about seven minutes...[Content truncated]

website_content.content:
Is Adam Sandler funny in real life? Or just in movies?
When did Adam Sandler stop being funny?
Right around the time we started growing up.
Adam Sandler was never funny. We were just younger, less mature and way less picky. His two biggest hits, Happy Gilmore and Billy Madison were high school favorites amongst my classmates. We all thought those movies were so hilarious, we went around quoting lines from them.
Had those movies come out today on Netflix, they’d get the same terrible reviews as Sandler’s latest string of flops.
!
The saddest part about growing up is realizing someone or something was never as funny as you remembered- you were just younger then.
But it’s hard to hate on a dude that’s super loyal to his group of friends. Thanks to Sandler, many of his less talented homies stay employed year round.
Are Adam Sandler films just plain stupid?
Basically, yes.
And those that think some of his earlier work was funnier were just younger when they watched it.
In one movie he's an adult that repeats grade school in order to inherit his father’s money.
In another, he adopts a kid to impress his ex-girlfriend.
He played the role of inbred football star.
He also played a hockey player turned pro golfer.
Let's not forget the one where he's an...
What do few people know about actor Adam Sandler's personal life?
Adam Sandler told in a 2017 interview that his daughters aren't big fans of his movies!
!
The actor explained that they always ask to see a movie of him, but give up on watching halfway through.
"I do. Because they beg to see \ So I show them \ and they see it every time, about 20 minutes, and then I see them dispersing, and I hear them. They get nervous to say, but they ask 'Can we see something else?'"
The girls were still young when the interview took place, they were 7 and 11 years old. Therefore, the actor believes that it was a matter of time before his offspring came to love his comedies.
But what about you, do you like the Adam Sandler movies or not?

I have driven across the country 5 times, been to more than 40 states, lived in 5 of them and I can tell you that on the level of beauty, New Jersey is simply average.
!
A lot of New Jersey is basic suburbia. It suffers from the same issues that northern suburbs do. Cold winters will crack up the roads and fill them with salt stain. Late winter in Jersey feels really dingy. But spring looks beautiful. Unlike Southwestern suburbs, we have huge lush trees to line our streets.
!
New Jersey beaches are gorgeous. I have been to many of the best beaches in the country and New Jersey ranks in the top 4 or 5 states for beaches. As others mentioned, the Shore is much more than Seaside Heights. It's 217 miles long and has fancy dancy Victorian wannabes like Cape May, slightly trashy but fun places like Point Pleasant, and beaches where you only meet residents like Mantoloking. There are wildlife preserves, boaters enclaves, and towns full of nice, working class families.
!
The Appalachian Trail runs through New Jersey. We have lovely parks and mountains to hike through. You will find more challenging trails in some other states, but Jersey is well-suited to the casual hiker.
!
Did you know New Jersey has lots of farms? We're particularly well known for our tomatoes and eggplants, but we also produce excellent corn and other products. Sections of Jersey, especially in the West, are known as farm country. I won't claim that we have the best or prettiest farms, but they're certainly pretty enough not to be the armpit.
States like Maine and Michigan have lush deep forests that are beautiful. New Mexico and Wyoming have interesting, exotic landscapes. Hawaii and California are beautiful, sunny places. New Jersey is not amazing, but it is simply not the Armpit of America. It has some beauty, some eyesores, and mostly just okay. It is an average state.
And don't go insulting us culturally or I will sic on you Frank Sinatra, Jack Nicholson, Queen Latifah, Kevin Spacey, Buzz Aldrin, Dorothy Parker, Meryl Streep, Norman Mailer, Ice-T, Stephen Crane, and Count Basie.
